  "prompt": "What is the magnitude of the force applied by the body on an object due to law of inertia?",
  "response": "The law of inertia, also known as Newton's First Law of Motion, states that an object will remain at rest or in uniform motion unless acted upon by an external force. The law itself does not specifically define the magnitude of a force; rather, it describes the inherent resistance of an object to changes in its state of motion.\n\nTo determine the magnitude of force applied on an object due to inertia, we need to consider external forces that might act on it. The force applied \\( F \\) can be calculated using Newton's Second Law of Motion:\n\n\\[ F = m \\cdot a \\]\n\nwhere:\n- \\( m \\) is the mass of the object,\n- \\( a \\) is the acceleration of the object.\n\nThis equation shows that the magnitude of the force is directly proportional to both the mass of the object and its acceleration.",
